ðŸ”¥ What is the subprocess Module in Python?
The subprocess module lets Python run system commands (Linux, Windows, macOS) directly from your script.
You can use it to:
Execute shell commands
Capture command output
Run multiple commands in pipelines
Handle errors
Automate admin tasks
This is SUPER useful for DevOps engineers!

ðŸŸ¢ Basic Example â€” Run a Command
import subprocess
result = subprocess.run(["ls", "-l"], capture_output=True, text=True)
print(result.stdout)

ðŸ‘‰ Explanation:
subprocess.run([...]) â†’ runs a command
["ls", "-l"] â†’ list directory with details
capture_output=True â†’ captures output instead of showing in terminal
text=True â†’ returns output as string
result.stdout â†’ command output
result.stderr â†’ errors (if any)

ðŸŸ£ Example: Check OS Name Using Command
import subprocess
cmd = ["uname", "-a"]
output = subprocess.run(cmd, capture_output=True, text=True)
print("System Info:", output.stdout)

ðŸ”¥ Example: Run a Shell Command (like piped commands)
import subprocess
command = "df -h | grep /dev"
result = subprocess.run(command, shell=True, capture_output=True, text=True)
print(result.stdout)

âš ï¸ Note:
shell=True allows pipes (|), redirection (>) etc.
ðŸ”¥ Example: Capture Errors
import subprocess
result = subprocess.run(["cat", "file_that_does_not_exist.txt"],
                        capture_output=True, text=True)
print("STDOUT:", result.stdout)
print("STDERR:", result.stderr)
print("Return Code:", result.returncode)

Output:
Return code 0 = success
Non-zero = error

ðŸš€ Example: Run a Command and Get Output Directly (check_output)
import subprocess
output = subprocess.check_output(["hostname"], text=True)
print("Hostname:", output)

âš¡ Example: Run a Command That Needs Input
import subprocess
process = subprocess.Popen(["cat"], stdin=subprocess.PIPE, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, text=True)
out, err = process.communicate("Hello from Python!")
print(out)| Function            

ðŸŽ¯ Most Common Functions in subprocess
| --------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| `subprocess.run()`          | Run a command, get return code/output |
| `subprocess.check_output()` | Run command and return only output    |
| `subprocess.Popen()`        | Full control over process (advanced)  |
| `communicate()`             | Send input & get output               |

ðŸŽ¯ Most Common Functions in subprocess

